&lt;br&gt;
I totally missed this.  I knew about the 3 years but did not catch that it was 17 years before he appeared in Antioch.  Shouldn't be surprizing as Moses was 40 years in preparation for his calling.&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Tracking Paul in the years before his appearance in Antioch is dicey. The places we look for details of his life come up blank on the 17 years following his encounter with Jesus outside Damascus.&lt;/p&gt;&#xd;
&lt;p&gt;He makes one reference, the same place where Paul gives more verses on his life than anywhere else – Galatians 1:11-2:1. The verses about these 17 years state that after returning from Arabia to Damascus, it was three years before he went to Jerusalem, to meet with Peter, and then he says that 14 years more passed before he returned to Jerusalem. This latter visit was for the well-publicized conference with James about circumcising Gentile believers.&lt;/p&gt;&#xd;
&lt;p&gt;He does say that during these years he was in Syria and Cilicia. What was this great apostle doing during this expanse of time?&lt;/p&gt;&#xd;
&lt;p&gt;The answer is – we don’t know!&lt;/p&gt;&#xd;
&lt;p&gt;Anything beyond that is speculation.&lt;/p&gt;&#xd;
&lt;p&gt;Allow me to speculate!&lt;/p&gt;&#xd;
&lt;p&gt;The fundamental Gospel issues were clear. He entered this time period with a deeper knowledge of the Gospel, of the issues of Jewish exclusivism, of Gentile inclusion. After three years of study he had a profound grasp of grace, justification, and the universal intention of God’s kingdom. Also, he located himself in the provinces of Syria and Cilicia, whose boundaries stretch from Damascus in the south to the eastern edge of Galatia in the north and west. In the light of Paul’s later travels, this is not a huge territory, but for the commencement of his apostleship a reasonable chunk.&lt;/p&gt;&#xd;
&lt;p&gt;What would he be doing? My hunch is a phase of learning by good intention and failure, a phase of church planting, and a phase of concentration in and around Tarsus.&lt;/p&gt;&#xd;
&lt;p&gt;The first phase might have evidenced a strategy of evangelizing synagogues as the base for Gentile expansion. That is the good intention, but the failure would be the refusal and resistance of Jews, even followers of Jesus, to accept Gentiles.&lt;/p&gt;&#xd;
&lt;p&gt;The second phase of church planting would take him to the house church model around clusters of Gentile believers. Why not? He knew the area well, was well acquainted with the culture, knew the pagan ways he was confronting, and knew ways to witness to them. This was, after all, his calling.&lt;/p&gt;&#xd;
&lt;p&gt;The third phase can be documented. With the Spirit’s work in the city of Antioch, the believers there needed seasoned teachers and disciplers. The leaders of the church in Jerusalem knew this and commissioned Barnabas to find Paul and enlist his help for the Antioch church. Barnabas found him in Tarsus.&lt;/p&gt;&#xd;
&lt;p&gt;Tarsus was his home town, a plausible place for Paul to concentrate his efforts. What is surprising is the absence of any further reference to there being a church established there.&lt;/p&gt;&#xd;
&lt;p&gt;Further speculation – he wrote letters during this period. Maybe from Damascus to Tarsus, or from Issus on the route around the sea to Aleppo. Who knows and why not?&lt;/p&gt;&#xd;
&lt;p&gt;For certain we can assume that he was putting into practice many of the teachings and conclusions that we know from his later letters.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;a href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/missionomission.wordpress.com/263/" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;img border="0" alt="" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/missionomission.wordpress.com/263/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godelicious/missionomission.wordpress.com/263/" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;img border="0" alt="" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/delicious/missionomission.wordpress.com/263/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gofacebook/missionomission.wordpress.com/263/" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;img border="0" alt="" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/facebook/missionomission.wordpress.com/263/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gotwitter/missionomission.wordpress.com/263/" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;img border="0" alt="" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/twitter/missionomission.wordpress.com/263/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gostumble/missionomission.wordpress.com/263/" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;img border="0" alt="" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/stumble/missionomission.wordpress.com/263/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godigg/missionomission.wordpress.com/263/" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;img border="0" alt="" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/digg/missionomission.wordpress.com/263/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/goreddit/missionomission.wordpress.com/263/" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;img border="0" alt="" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/reddit/missionomission.wordpress.com/263/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;img border="0" alt="" src="http://stats.wordpress.com/b.gif?host=missionomission.org&amp;amp;blog=18910552&amp;amp;post=263&amp;amp;subd=missionomission&amp;amp;ref=&amp;amp;feed=1" width="1" height="1"&gt;
</content><author gr:unknown-author="true"><name>(author unknown)</name></author><gr:annotation><content type="html">I totally missed this.  I knew about the 3 years but did not catch that it was 17 years before he appeared in Antioch.  Shouldn't be surprizing as Moses was 40 years in preparation for his calling.</content><author gr:user-id="05017898453493988347" gr:profile-id="107545282889348123759"><name>Pat</name></author></gr:annotation><source gr:stream-id="user/05017898453493988347/source/com.google/link"><id>tag:google.com,2005:reader/user/05017898453493988347/source/com.google/link</id><title type="html">Mission Omission</title><link rel="alternate" href="http://missionomission.org" type="text/html"/></source></entry><entry gr:crawl-timestamp-msec="1317123441272"><id gr:original-id="http://missionofgod.posterous.com/mission-of-god-in-the-nt-1-corinthians">tag:google.com,2005:reader/item/5846640877e28c39</id><title type="html">Mission of God in the NT: 1 Corinthians</title><published>2011-09-19T13:00:00Z</published><updated>2011-09-19T13:00:00Z</updated><link rel="alternate" href="http://missionofgod.posterous.com/mission-of-god-in-the-nt-1-corinthians" type="text/html"/><summary xml:base="http://missionofgod.posterous.com/" type="html">&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;1 Corinthians: Persuasive Cross-cultural Witness&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the two letters Paul wrote to the church he planted at Corinth, he manifests an awareness that his was a cross-cultural missionary church planting mission.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;As he deals with divisions rooted in a cultural attraction to speakers with cleverness pursued with rhetorical technique (“wisdom of word,” 1 Cor 1:17), he points to a proclamation of the gospel which addresses the standards of two ethnic groups: Jews and Greeks (1:18-25).&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;Jews seek “signs”; Greeks seek “wisdom.”&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;Paul’s strategy is to preach a gospel of the cross which is subversive of both values: a scandal to Jews and foolishness to Greeks.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;For only in that way can a truly culturally transformative gospel be transplanted into their hearts.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;For as they receive it their faith will not rest in the wisdom of men but in the power of God (2:4-5).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Not only is the gospel and the Spirit’s saving power transcultural, the congregations&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;formed reflect a transcultural unity, as well as, a multi-ethnic diversity.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;So, Paul can use the physical body—members imagery and declare, “For, as the body is one and has many members, and although all the members of the body are many, the body is one, so also is Christ.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;For, indeed, we all by one Spirit have been baptized into one body, whether Jews or Greeks, whether slaves or freedman, and we all have been made to drink of one Spirit” (1 Cor 12:12-13).&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;Unity in the midst of mult-ethnic diversity, all because God’s plan for applying salvation involves an invitation with a universal reach to every culture and tribe and nation and tongue.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Paul in 1 Corinthians teaches us that the gospel is multi-culturally persuasive and births a unified multi-cultural church.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;Only the culturally transformative power and wisdom of God can do this.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.ciu.edu/seminary/faculty/bio.php?id=95"&gt;Dr. William Larkin&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;Professor of Greek and NT, &lt;a href="http://www.ciu.edu"&gt;Columbia International University&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;What can we learn from Paul's strategy to be "a scandal" and "foolishness" to the Corinthians? What are current barriers to growing multi-ethnic congregations, such as the one in Corinth? Please share your thoughts below...&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
	
&lt;/p&gt;

