									&lt;/div&gt;
				We have an inherent selfishness about us.  It's why heroes in movies will sacrifice the world for the person s/he loves and we all find that romantic instead of disturbing.  It's why we have a tendency to care a lot less about a genocide than a friend with cancer.  As David Ropeik points out in an article for Psychology Today, we have a statistical numbness that urges us to care more about the problems of an individual than the problems of many. 				&lt;a href="http://lifehacker.com/5831013/why-you-dont-care-about-the-deaths-of-millions-of-people" title="Click here to read more about Why You Don&amp;#39;t Care About the Deaths of Millions of People [Psychology]"&gt;More »&lt;/a&gt;
